\v 2 Eve replied \w to|strong="H6086"\w* \w the|strong="H6086"\w* \w serpent|strong="H5175"\w*, “We can eat \w from|strong="H6086"\w* \w the|strong="H6086"\w* \w trees|strong="H6086"\w* \w in|strong="H6086"\w* \w the|strong="H6086"\w* \w garden|strong="H1588"\w*, but not \w the|strong="H6086"\w* \w fruit|strong="H6529"\w* \w from|strong="H6086"\w* \w the|strong="H6086"\w* \w tree|strong="H6086"\w* \w in|strong="H6086"\w* \w the|strong="H6086"\w* middle \w of|strong="H6086"\w* \w the|strong="H6086"\w* \w garden|strong="H1588"\w*.  
\v 3 \w God|strong="H3808"\w* told \w us|strong="H6435"\w*, ‘\w You|strong="H3808"\w* mustn't eat \w from|strong="H4480"\w* \w that|strong="H4480"\w* \w tree|strong="H6086"\w*, \w or|strong="H3808"\w* \w even|strong="H3808"\w* \w touch|strong="H5060"\w* \w it|strong="H8432"\w*, \w otherwise|strong="H6435"\w* \w you|strong="H3808"\w*'ll \w die|strong="H4191"\w*.’”\f + \fr 3:3 \ft “Otherwise you'll die.” The word used for “otherwise,” can indicate a possibility of something happening, rather than absolute certainty. So the phrase could be translated, “otherwise you might die,” a difference from God's clear prohibition, also claiming that God had said the fruit was not to be touched.\f*   
\p
